# Code Philosophy

- Write production-quality code. Prefer readability over cleverness.
- Every class and function has a single responsibility.
- Follow SOLID principles. Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions and over-engineering.
- Never duplicate business logic.

# Clean Architecture

Every module must follow Clean Architecture. Dependencies always point inward.

```text
feature/
  domain/        # business logic, interfaces — no data/presentation imports
  data/          # repositories, APIs, persistence
  presentation/  # UI logic only
  di/            # dependency wiring
  tests/
```

- Domain must never depend on Data or Presentation.
- Business logic belongs only in Domain.
- Presentation contains UI logic only.

# Package-First Development

Organize by feature/package, never by technical layer alone.

**Backend** (`backend/internal/` or `services/backend/internal/`):

```text
internal/
  auth/
    handler/ service/ repository/ model/ dto/ mapper/
  user/
  notification/
```

**KMP** (`mobile/shared/`):

```text
feature/
  auth/
  user/
  notification/
```

Before creating a new package: inspect the repo tree, search existing packages, extend when appropriate. Never create duplicate packages.

# Helper Functions

Minimize helpers and utility files. Do not create helpers for trivial logic.

Extract a helper only when:
- reused in multiple places, or
- it significantly improves readability.

Keep logic close to where it is used. Avoid generic utility packages with unrelated methods.

# Reuse Existing Code

Before writing new code:

1. Search the project.
2. Search existing packages.
3. Search existing services and repositories.
4. Reuse or extend existing implementations.

Never duplicate code. If a reusable abstraction exists, extend it.
